            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <h2>When to Use This Guide</h2>
<p>This SOP applies to overseas teams managing multiple ad accounts across platforms like Meta, Google, and TikTok. A standardized reconciliation process helps identify issues like failed recharge, abnormal spend, and invoice mismatches promptly, reducing financial risk.</p>
<h2>Pre-Reconciliation Preparation</h2>
<h3>Collect Essential Data</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Platform Spend Reports</strong>: Download spend breakdowns for the period, including account ID, spend amount, currency, and date</li>
<li><strong>Recharge Records</strong>: Internal recharge applications, third-party payment receipts, and platform confirmation screenshots</li>
<li><strong>Invoice List</strong>: Scanned or electronic invoices from platforms, organized by account and period</li>
<li><strong>Exchange Rates</strong>: Required for multi-currency transactions—record rates for both recharge and spend dates</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p>Recommendation: Set up a shared folder with a "Account-Month" directory structure to store original documents for easy reference.</p>
</blockquote>
<h2>Daily Reconciliation Workflow (Execute Daily)</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Verify Recharge Arrival</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Step</th>
<th>Action</th>
<th>Red Flag</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>1</td>
<td>Export yesterday's recharge records</td>
<td>Zero amount flagged</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>2</td>
<td>Log in to platform backend to confirm balance change</td>
<td>Balance unchanged</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>3</td>
<td>Compare recharge amount with received amount</td>
<td>Difference over 1%</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>4</td>
<td>Log exception transaction IDs</td>
<td>Pending follow-up</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3>Step 2: Download Spend Reports</h3>
<p>Log into each ad platform and export yesterday's spend data. Use native platform reports to avoid delays from third-party tools.</p>
<h3>Step 3: Complete Daily Reconciliation Log</h3>
<p>Use a standardized template to record: date, account name, recharge amount, spend amount, account balance, and notes. Mark "No Activity" if there were no changes that day to maintain reconciliation continuity.</p>
<h2>Monthly Reconciliation Workflow (Complete by the 5th of Each Month)</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Summarize Recharge Data</h3>
<p>Aggregate all recharge records for the month by account and calculate total recharge amount. List refunds or balance returns separately.</p>
<h3>Step 2: Summarize Spend Data</h3>
<p>Export full-month spend reports from each platform. Verify that the billing cycle covers the complete calendar month. Some platforms bill by advertiser timezone—align this with your finance monthly close cycle.</p>
<h3>Step 3: Verify Account Balance</h3>
<p><strong>Core Formula</strong>: Ending Balance = Beginning Balance + Monthly Recharge - Monthly Spend</p>
<p>Example (SaaS App):</p>
<ul>
<li>Beginning balance: $5,000</li>
<li>Monthly recharge: $10,000</li>
<li>Monthly spend: $8,500</li>
<li>Expected ending balance: $6,500</li>
</ul>
<p>If the platform backend shows a different balance, trace the difference entry by entry.</p>
<h3>Step 4: Verify Invoices</h3>
<ol>
<li>Confirm invoice billing name matches your registered company name</li>
<li>Verify invoice amount matches the platform statement</li>
<li>Check that invoice currency matches the recharge currency</li>
<li>Validate invoice authenticity (via platform official channels or tax authority website)</li>
<li>Bind invoice to corresponding recharge record and archive</li>
</ol>
<h3>Step 5: Generate Reconciliation Report</h3>
<p>Output a monthly reconciliation summary containing:</p>
<ul>
<li>Account-level recharge/spend/balance summary</li>
<li>Invoice verification status</li>
<li>Exception details and resolution progress</li>
<li>Exchange rate variance notes (if applicable)</li>
</ul>
<h2>Handling Common Discrepancies</h2>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Discrepancy Type</th>
<th>Possible Cause</th>
<th>Recommended Action</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Recharge not received</td>
<td>Payment delay, incorrect details</td>
<td>Keep records and contact platform support or agent</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Abnormal spend</td>
<td>Data sync delay, timezone difference</td>
<td>Wait 24-48 hours and recheck</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Invoice underbilling</td>
<td>Mismatch between billing and invoice cycles</td>
<td>Verify and request amendment or adjust booking period</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Exchange rate variance</td>
<td>Different rates on recharge vs. spend dates</td>
<td>Apply your finance policy's conversion method</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h2>Recommendations for Efficiency</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Standardized Templates</strong>: Create pre-built Excel templates or use internal systems with fixed field formats</li>
<li><strong>Automation Tools</strong>: Some third-party finance management tools support API integration to automatically pull recharge and spend data</li>
<li><strong>Regular Training</strong>: Ensure new team members master the reconciliation process to reduce human errors</li>
<li><strong>Exception Alerts</strong>: Set up alerts for failed recharges, spend spikes, and other anomalies to catch issues early</li>
</ol>
<p>Unified reconciliation is not only a financial compliance requirement but also the foundation for optimizing ad spend cost control. When operations and finance teams collaborate on this process, they can effectively reduce discrepancies and provide reliable data for downstream ROI analysis.</p>
